<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,831]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,573,599]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[334,468,574,599]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Vekunta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bri">
<emphasis box="[334,468,574,599]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Vekunta bri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from many other 
<taxonomicName box="[766,859,574,599]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Vekunta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[766,859,574,599]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Vekunta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by its colour and body shape. Compared to externally similar species, the structures of the male genitalia (anal tube, aedeagus, see 
<figureCitation box="[1211,1298,612,638]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="22.[151,255,1291,1315]" captionTargetBox="[188,1389,186,1250]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[172,1404,147,1275]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 16. Vekunta bri: A – C aedeagus, (A) left lateral (B) ventral (C) ventrolateral; D, E anal tube; F, G genital style, (F) ventral (G) left lateral; H genital capsule." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190097/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Figs 
<number box="[1270,1298,612,638]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
A–E) allow easy identification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,831]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,689,715]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[326,419,689,714]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Vekunta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[326,419,689,714]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Vekunta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a diverse genus in the subtropical and tropical regions of 
<collectingCountry box="[1119,1179,689,715]" name="India" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">India</collectingCountry>
and Asia, comprising about 
<number box="[228,259,728,754]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="35.0">35</number>
species (Bourgoin 
<number box="[500,567,728,754]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="2008.0">2008</number>
). The generic placement of this new species into 
<taxonomicName box="[1181,1278,728,753]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Vekunta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1181,1278,728,753]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Vekunta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, is tentative. It is based mainly on the characters given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fennah" box="[802,977,767,793]" pageId="16" pageNumber="26" refString="Fennah, R. G. (1952) On the generic classification of Derbidae (Fulgoroidea), with descriuptions of new neotropical species. Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society London 103, 109 - 170." type="journal article" year="1952">
Fennah (
<number box="[904,968,767,793]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="1952.0">1952</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
; both 
<taxonomicName box="[1050,1143,767,792]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Vekunta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1050,1143,767,792]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Vekunta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the family 
<taxonomicName box="[1329,1436,767,793]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Derbidae</taxonomicName>
as a whole still await a revision and comprehensive phylogenetic analysis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
